<?php
$qualityOptions = array("a" => "Reliability", "b" => "Validity", "c" => "Internal validity", "d" => "External validity", "e" => "Ecological validity");

return array(
    "overview" => "Random assignment is only one part of a trustworthy study. Blinding, measurement quality, order control, operational definitions, pilot testing, and careful handling of missing data determine whether a result is consistent, meaningful, and transferable.",
    "objectives" => array("Explain single and double blinding and allocation concealment.", "Recognize repeated measures, order effects, carryover, and counterbalancing.", "Distinguish reliability from validity and internal from external validity.", "Write operational definitions and identify measurement error.", "Explain the purposes of pilot studies and evaluate missing-data risks."),
    "prerequisites" => array("Understand treatment, response, control, and random assignment.", "Recognize matched pairs and repeated measures.", "Identify bias and confounding."),
    "vocabulary" => array(
        array("Blinding", "Keeping treatment identity hidden from participants, evaluators, or both."), array("Allocation concealment", "Preventing the person enrolling units from predicting the next assignment."),
        array("Repeated measures", "Collecting several outcomes from the same unit."), array("Order effect", "A response change caused by treatment sequence rather than treatment identity."),
        array("Counterbalancing", "Varying treatment order across participants."), array("Reliability", "Consistency of a measurement under similar conditions."),
        array("Validity", "The degree to which a measurement or study captures what it claims to capture."), array("Internal validity", "How credibly the response difference can be attributed to treatment."),
        array("External validity", "How well results apply beyond the studied units and setting."), array("Operational definition", "An exact rule for measuring or classifying a variable.")
    ),
    "sections" => array(
        array("title" => "Blinding and Expectations", "content" => array(
            "<p>Knowing a treatment can change behaviour, reporting, and evaluation. <strong>Blinding</strong> limits that influence. In a single-blind study, participants commonly do not know which condition they receive, although terminology varies by field. In a double-blind study, participants and the people who directly evaluate outcomes do not know assignments. A separate team may still hold the assignment code for safety and analysis.</p>",
            "<p>Blinding reduces placebo effects, unequal encouragement, and observer expectations. It is easiest when treatments can look alike. It may be impossible when comparing visible teaching schedules or user interfaces. Researchers can still blind outcome scorers, use objective automated measures, give scripted instructions, and analyse coded groups before revealing labels.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Allocation concealment</strong> protects an earlier point: the person enrolling participants should not predict the next assignment. Otherwise, they might intentionally or unconsciously direct certain people into one group. Concealed random allocation and blinding solve different problems: concealment protects assignment, while blinding protects behaviour and measurement afterward.</p>",
            array("type" => "warning", "label" => "Do not overclaim", "html" => "<p>Calling a study double-blind is not a complete quality guarantee. Poor randomization, weak measurement, missing data, or selective reporting can still undermine it.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Repeated Measures and Order", "content" => array(
            "<p>Repeated-measures designs collect more than one response from the same individual. They are efficient because each person acts as their own comparison, reducing stable differences in skill, speed, or preference. They also introduce dependence: responses from the same person are connected and should not be treated as independent observations.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Order effects</strong> occur when sequence changes the response. Practice may improve a second score, fatigue may lower it, and the first treatment may carry over into the second. A website user may complete the second task faster simply because the task structure is now familiar. If everyone receives A then B, treatment B is confounded with being second.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Counterbalancing</strong> varies order, often assigning half to A-then-B and half to B-then-A. More treatments may use randomized orders or balanced sequences. Comparable fresh tasks and a suitable break can reduce practice and carryover. These choices should be planned before data collection, not explained away afterward.</p>",
            array("type" => "example", "label" => "What counterbalancing cannot fix", "html" => "<p>If Treatment A permanently changes the participant, merely reversing order for half may not remove carryover. Researchers may need separate groups or a longer washout period.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Reliability and Validity", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Reliability</strong> asks whether a measure is consistent. A scale that gives 60.1, 60.0, and 60.1 kg under unchanged conditions is reliable. <strong>Validity</strong> asks whether the measure captures the intended quantity. If that scale is miscalibrated by 5 kg, it is reliable but not accurate or valid for true weight. Consistency is valuable, but consistent error remains error.</p>",
            "<p>A survey intended to measure academic motivation may be unreliable if answers swing with minor wording changes. It may be reliable but invalid if it asks only how many hours students sit at a desk, which can reflect workload, distractions, or available time instead of motivation. Evidence for validity comes from the connection between the operational measure and the intended concept.</p>",
            "<p><strong>Internal validity</strong> concerns the causal comparison inside a study: were confounders controlled and groups treated comparably? <strong>External validity</strong> concerns application to other people, places, times, and conditions. A tightly controlled lab study can have high internal validity but limited external validity. <strong>Ecological validity</strong> specifically asks whether the setting resembles the real environment where the behaviour occurs.</p>",
            "<table><thead><tr><th>Question</th><th>Quality</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Would measurement repeat consistently?</td><td>Reliability</td></tr><tr><td>Does it measure the intended concept?</td><td>Validity</td></tr><tr><td>Can treatment explain the difference?</td><td>Internal validity</td></tr><tr><td>Do results transfer?</td><td>External validity</td></tr></tbody></table>"
        )),
        array("title" => "Measurement and Operational Definitions", "content" => array(
            "<p><strong>Measurement error</strong> is the difference between a measured and true value. Instrument error, poor calibration, rounding, inconsistent observers, data-entry mistakes, vague categories, and inaccurate self-report all contribute. Random measurement error adds variability; systematic measurement error creates bias. Recording reaction time with a hand-operated stopwatch may vary around the truth, while a clock that always runs slow creates directional error.</p>",
            "<p>An <strong>operational definition</strong> states exactly how a variable is measured or classified. \"Student success\" is too vague. \"The percentage of assigned tasks submitted by 11:59 p.m. on their due date during a six-week period\" identifies unit, rule, and time frame. Clear definitions improve repeatability and let readers decide whether the measure is valid.</p>",
            "<p>Operational choices can change conclusions. Measuring app engagement as logins rewards frequent brief visits; measuring minutes may reward long inactive sessions; measuring completed tasks may better match productive use. Researchers should justify the measure, use the same rule for all groups, calibrate instruments, train observers, and document any changes.</p>",
            array("type" => "definition", "label" => "Strong definition checklist", "html" => "<p>Name what is counted or measured, the unit, the time period, the source, and the rule for borderline cases.</p>")
        )),
        array("title" => "Pilot Studies, Missing Data, and Data Quality", "content" => array(
            "<p>A <strong>pilot study</strong> is a small trial run of the planned study. It tests instructions, timing, recruitment, surveys, equipment, randomization, and data storage. A pilot can reveal that students interpret a question differently, a task takes too long, a sensor drops readings, or a treatment is impractical. Its purpose is to improve the final design, not to search repeatedly for a promising result.</p>",
            "<p>Missing data arise when participants skip questions, leave the study, equipment fails, records are incomplete, or data are entered incorrectly. Missingness becomes especially dangerous when it relates to treatment or outcome. If students struggling with a program are more likely to leave, analysing completers only will make the program look more successful.</p>",
            "<p>Data quality includes accuracy, completeness, consistency, timeliness, and relevance. Researchers should record why data are missing, compare dropout rates across groups, define exclusions before analysis, and report limitations. Advanced calculations cannot reconstruct information that was never measured well. Quality is built during design and collection.</p>",
            array("type" => "note", "label" => "Pilot versus main study", "html" => "<p>When a pilot leads to major changes, its data usually should not be silently combined with final-study data because participants experienced different procedures.</p>")
        ))
    ),
    "worked_examples" => array(
        array("title" => "Blind interface scoring", "scenario" => "Users know which interface they use, but independent evaluators score recorded task errors without seeing interface labels.", "steps" => array("Participant blinding is impossible because interfaces look different.", "Coded recordings can blind evaluators to treatment.", "Automated timing and scripted instructions further reduce observer influence.", "The study should describe exactly who was blinded instead of using an unclear label."), "conclusion" => "Partial blinding and objective measurement can improve a visible-treatment experiment."),
        array("title" => "Counterbalancing a typing test", "scenario" => "Every student types with Keyboard A and B, and typing speed is the response.", "steps" => array("This is repeated measures, so each student provides paired times.", "Typing second may benefit from practice or suffer fatigue.", "Randomly assign half to A-B and half to B-A, use equally difficult text, and provide the same break.", "Compare within-student differences while checking whether order changes the result."), "conclusion" => "Counterbalancing separates keyboard effects from being first or second."),
        array("title" => "Reliable but invalid", "scenario" => "A bathroom scale gives nearly identical readings but is always 4 kg too high.", "steps" => array("Repeated readings are consistent, so reliability is high.", "The readings do not match true weight because calibration is wrong.", "The measure is systematically inaccurate and therefore not valid for true weight.", "Calibrate against a known standard before collecting study data."), "conclusion" => "Reliability is necessary for many measurements but does not guarantee validity."),
        array("title" => "Operationalizing engagement", "scenario" => "A team wants to measure meaningful engagement with a homework app.", "steps" => array("Define the concept rather than relying on the word engagement.", "Choose a behaviour aligned with the goal, such as assignments opened and submitted by deadline.", "Specify a four-week window and rules for duplicate or deleted assignments.", "Use the same extraction rule for all users."), "conclusion" => "A repeatable definition could be 'the proportion of assigned tasks opened and submitted by the recorded deadline during four weeks.'"),
    ),
    "misconceptions" => array(
        array("Double-blind means nobody knows anything.", "An authorized team may hold treatment codes; the key is that participants and direct evaluators do not know during relevant stages."),
        array("Reliable means correct.", "A measure can repeat the same biased value and remain invalid."),
        array("A realistic setting guarantees a causal result.", "Ecological realism does not replace random assignment and control."),
        array("Repeated measures create more independent participants.", "Several observations from one person remain related."),
        array("Missing data only reduce sample size.", "If missingness relates to response or treatment, it can systematically bias results."),
        array("A pilot is a small final study.", "Its main purpose is to test and improve procedures before the main data collection.")
    ),
    "why" => array("A study can be randomized yet still fail because outcomes were measured inconsistently, evaluators knew the expected result, or the weakest participants disappeared from the data. Design quality is a chain, and each element supports interpretation.", "These ideas also apply outside formal research: reliable website analytics need stable definitions, fair grading needs consistent rubrics, and business decisions need complete, timely, relevant records."),
    "knowledge_check" => array(
        stats_classify("kc1", "A scale repeats nearly the same reading under unchanged conditions.", $qualityOptions, "a", "<p>Consistency under repetition describes reliability.</p>", "Ask about consistency or meaning.", "foundational", array("reliability")),
        stats_classify("kc2", "A controlled experiment isolates treatment as the plausible cause.", $qualityOptions, "c", "<p>Attributing the response internally to treatment concerns internal validity.</p>", "Inside-study causation.", "foundational", array("internal validity")),
        stats_classify("kc3", "A study result applies to students in different schools and years.", $qualityOptions, "d", "<p>Transfer beyond the original study concerns external validity.</p>", "Think beyond the study boundary.", "foundational", array("external validity"))
    ),
    "guided_practice" => array(
        stats_written("g1", "short-response", "Explain why evaluator blinding matters even when the response uses a rubric.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> A rubric reduces subjectivity, but an evaluator who knows treatment may interpret borderline work differently. Coded work prevents expectations from consistently favouring one group.</p>", "Rubrics still require judgment.", "proficient", array("blinding")),
        stats_written("g2", "short-response", "Describe counterbalancing for three treatments A, B, and C.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Assign participants across varied orders such as ABC, ACB, BAC, BCA, CAB, and CBA, with roughly equal numbers when practical, so no treatment is always first or last.</p>", "Vary treatment positions.", "advanced", array("counterbalancing")),
        stats_classify("g3", "A motivation survey actually measures only hours available after school.", $qualityOptions, "b", "<p>The measure may not capture the intended construct, which is a validity problem.</p>", "Does it measure what it claims?", "proficient", array("validity")),
        stats_classify("g4", "A silent lab typing task may not represent a noisy classroom.", $qualityOptions, "e", "<p>The setting differs from the real environment, raising ecological-validity concerns.</p>", "Focus on realism of setting.", "proficient", array("ecological validity")),
        stats_written("g5", "short-response", "Write an operational definition for on-time homework completion.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> The number of assignments uploaded to the school system no later than the recorded due date and time, divided by all assignments due during the four-week study.</p>", "Include count, deadline rule, denominator, and time period.", "proficient", array("operational definition")),
        stats_written("g6", "error-analysis", "A student says dropouts only make an experiment less precise. Explain the missing risk.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Dropout can create bias if leaving is related to treatment or response. For example, struggling users may leave one treatment more often, making remaining users look unusually successful.</p>", "Ask who leaves and why.", "advanced", array("missing data")),
        stats_written("g7", "short-response", "Name two things a pilot study could reveal.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> It could reveal confusing instructions, unrealistic timing, recruitment problems, broken equipment, unexpected missing fields, or an impractical treatment procedure.</p>", "Think through the study from invitation to stored data.", "foundational", array("pilot")),
        stats_written("g8", "short-response", "Distinguish allocation concealment from blinding.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Allocation concealment prevents recruiters from predicting the next treatment before assignment. Blinding hides assigned treatment from participants or evaluators after assignment.</p>", "Before versus after assignment.", "advanced", array("blinding"))
    ),
    "independent_practice" => array(
        stats_classify("i1", "Different graders give very similar scores using one rubric.", $qualityOptions, "a", "<p>Agreement under the same conditions indicates reliability.</p>", "Consistency across graders.", "foundational", array("reliability")),
        stats_classify("i2", "A highly controlled result may not apply outside one specialist school.", $qualityOptions, "d", "<p>The concern is generalization, or external validity.</p>", "Beyond the original group.", "foundational", array("external validity")),
        stats_written("i3", "short-response", "Identify a likely order effect when students solve similar puzzles twice.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Practice from the first puzzle may improve performance on the second regardless of treatment; fatigue could also reduce the second result.</p>", "Second attempt differs because it is second.", "proficient", array("order effects")),
        stats_written("i4", "short-response", "How can researchers reduce observer measurement error?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Use calibrated instruments, train observers, write a clear rubric, test agreement, blind evaluators, automate objective measurements when suitable, and audit data entry.</p>", "Standardize both tools and people.", "proficient", array("measurement error")),
        stats_written("i5", "short-response", "Explain why login count may be an invalid measure of productive app engagement.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Frequent logins can occur without meaningful work and may reflect technical interruptions. A measure tied to opened and completed assignments may better match productive engagement.</p>", "Connect the measure to the intended concept.", "proficient", array("validity")),
        stats_written("i6", "short-response", "A pilot changes instructions halfway through. Should all pilot data be merged into the final study?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Usually no. The procedures differ, so responses are not directly comparable. The pilot should document the change and the final study should restart with the fixed protocol unless a justified analysis plan says otherwise.</p>", "Different procedures can create different data.", "advanced", array("pilot")),
        stats_written("i7", "short-response", "Name five dimensions of data quality.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Accuracy, completeness, consistency, timeliness, and relevance.</p>", "Use the list from the final concept section.", "foundational", array("data quality")),
        stats_written("i8", "error-analysis", "A team says realistic website traffic means its A/B test has high internal validity. Evaluate.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Realistic traffic supports ecological or external relevance, not necessarily internal validity. Internal validity also requires fair random assignment, stable implementation, accurate outcomes, and limited differential missing data.</p>", "Realism and causal isolation are separate.", "advanced", array("validity")),
        stats_written("i9", "short-response", "Explain why data missing from one treatment group is especially concerning.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Differential missingness can make groups incomparable after randomization. If the reason for missing data relates to the response, the observed treatment difference may reflect who remained rather than treatment itself.</p>", "Compare missingness across treatments.", "advanced", array("missing data")),
        stats_written("i10", "short-response", "Audit a repeated-measures app test for blinding, order, measurement, and missing data.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> Randomize and counterbalance interface order, use comparable tasks, automate timing and error counts, blind any human scorers with coded recordings, define exclusions before testing, record failed sessions and dropouts, and report whether missingness differs by order or interface.</p>", "Check one protection for each named area.", "advanced", array("design audit"))
    ),
    "summary" => array("Blinding limits expectation effects; allocation concealment protects assignment before treatment.", "Repeated measures require attention to practice, fatigue, carryover, and order.", "Reliability means consistency; validity means measuring the intended concept.", "Internal validity concerns causal isolation, while external validity concerns transfer.", "Operational definitions, pilot testing, and transparent missing-data procedures build data quality."),
    "exit_ticket" => array(
        stats_written("e1", "short-response", "Give an example of a reliable but invalid measurement.", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> A miscalibrated scale that gives nearly identical readings but always reads 4 kg high is reliable but invalid for true weight.</p>", "Repeatable systematic error.", "proficient", array("reliability", "validity")),
        stats_written("e2", "short-response", "Why should an operational definition be written before data collection?", "<p><strong>Model answer:</strong> It ensures every unit is measured by the same rule, improves repeatability, and prevents researchers from changing the outcome definition after seeing results.</p>", "Consistency and protection from result-driven changes.", "proficient", array("operational definition"))
    )
);
